segments.text: The city could have got help from the government.
I know one night I was at a community meeting over in Brown and our representative in Washington was at that meeting and he told us that he could get us some help and I remember that I

In reply to that offer, I told him that we didn't want any help, that we would live within our means, and that we would hope to grow, but I personally didn't like the idea of somebody else carrying our load.
I've already told you we had no bonded indebtedness.
We took these utilities over and paid for them.
After a few years you see we got it done but we used the income from the water
and from the electricity to pay them off.
And we got out and owning those systems without having to borrow money.
But I did.
The first money that the city ever borrowed was when Ernest Langford, the man who succeeded me as mayor, came to me about a year after he had been in office
and asked me if I would loan them $500, which I did.
And as a friend to me, he says, now, this is going to be the last bill we pay back, so you can really make something out of it.
Now, that's, oh, my, I get to slide.
I don't know where to begin or where to quit.
I bet.
I bet he is.
Well, why did you decide to run for office?
Why did you decide to be the mayor?
I told these people when they came around.
They were good friends of mine.
I told them, I don't know where to thank you or insult you.
Some people came and asked you to be mayor?
Yes.
Who were they?
Well, Mr. Barton is the only one left.
Mr. Bonin was on that committee.
He came and asked me if I'd run.
And the faculty was on my side in all this trouble with the college and the board of directors.
The faculty was just, oh, they just were so pleased with me.
Because I got these roughnecks off of the freshmen.
And this school started to grow in.
And the faculty was with me.
But they were, they didn't dare say anything.
They didn't come out and publish that they were farming because the board of directors might have fired them because the board of directors wanted to keep the system.
They were all Aggies.
I remember one time I had a meeting with, the senior class had a meeting, they asked me to come to it over in the old YMCA.
The old YMCA used to have a chapel and that's all into rooms.
It's where a whole lot of the office work of the college is now.
But it's the one with the big steps.
Sure, I know where it is.
Well, you were saying that you were having a meeting.
Oh, I was having a meeting with these boys.
I remember old Joe Routt.
Joe Routt Boulevard's name for him.
He says, won't you please quit trying to change our school?
I said, Joe...
I said, Joe, this school doesn't belong to you.
It belongs to the state of Texas.
You don't have rights.
You don't have a right to do things you want to do and what these boys have been doing around here.
Somebody has to do something about it.
And I'm going to do something about it.
Because it's not right for you to think it's all right for you to run off these freshmen like you're doing.
Well, he said, we'd rather have 1,500 agas than 15,000 tea sippers.
I said, I'm just as tough as you are, and maybe a whole lot tougher.
So you haven't got anything to be proud of.
I respect A&M.
I love A&M.
I want to do something for A&M.
I've been here 12 years already.
And I'm determined to do it.
All right, they go over and tell Dr. Walton they want to get rid of me.
And then Dr. Walton asks the board of directors to come up here.
And the board of directors have a meeting.
And they ask for this senior, and this senior, and this senior, and this senior, or come down there, and they don't ask for me.
I went down there, and I said, listen, you came up here to investigate something, and I want you to start out with me, rather than not everybody else but me.
I'm doing something for you.
You can't hire.
You've had lots of commandants, and none of them have done what they ought to do.
You ought to know better yourselves.
You either want my what I want, or you don't want me.
Now, that's just up to you now.
You can just tell me to close out and go.
They didn't dare do it.
They would like to have done it, but the state of Texas is on my side, and they didn't dare do it.
And they just said, oh, you've done a wonderful job.
You saved us this last year $15,000 on broken up furniture and slats kicked out of doors.
These boys just knock off their screens and throw them away.
They just rough on everything.
They had no consideration for anybody else.
They took advantage of the situation and messed up the furniture.
Well, I told Dr. Walton they're going to quit that.
When I took the job, I said, now there's certain things, Dr. Walton, I'm going to see if they don't do.
I'm going to make them sign for this room, everything that's in it, just like it is.
And they are going to have to replace anything.
They're going to have to pay for it.
And I made them do it.
They didn't like that.
They didn't like a lot of things.
They made the freshmen stay in their rooms from the time they were out, unless they were out in some company sport or something like that.
They made them stay in their rooms.
They were room-bound after their last class.
They couldn't go to Brown.
They couldn't go visit somebody else.
They stayed in their thing so they could be there to run errands for the upperclassmen and things like that.
I talked to Dean Bolton and asked him, let's do something about some of these things.
He says, oh, well, let's don't be too in a hurry like that.
I said, now let's let them go to Brown after December the 10th, which is the first grade.
If they pass all the work due for December the 10th, I'm going to say that they ought to be allowed to leave that room and stay out until quarter to quarters.
Well, he wouldn't agree with me.
Next year, I didn't talk to him.
I just passed a rule and published it.
Freshman, if you are passing your work on December the 10th, you are a free man.
I don't want to see you in your room unless you're studying.
I rubbed it in on him.
Listen, I have gone up to that campus and found a sophomore drilling the freshman at 3 o'clock in the morning.
It was just a system that was too hard in running people away.
Huh?
It was something that was scaring people off.
Is that right?
Well, it was something to keep them from studying.
That's right.
They did everything they could to run them off.
They said, just like Joe Wright said, we're making aggies here.
Rough stuff, real stuff.
Texas A&M, as their chief yells,
And we were the bullies of the conference.
Nobody liked us.
They would crash the gate.
They'd just go to the games.
Unruly.
Nobody down here would do anything about it.
Well, I took the two or three army officers that were supposed to be working with the
and we told these people, now listen, don't you get caught up there without a, don't you get caught up there without a ticket.

Now that happened after we took the first football team to, well the first court trip went up to TCU and the Texas Hotel and don't go on if they didn't run off with all the towels and linen and, well it was the same thing, they wanted to take one man, Charles,
His name was, I can't think of it right now, his first name was Charles.
He was a senior, he took a floor lamp.
All we did, all we did was just, they always drilled on Thursday afternoon.
They were out with the army officers drilling.
Nobody in their rooms.
Didn't have anybody but cadets in those days.
Just military pure.
So we in the commandant's office, we had pass keys to every dormitory.
And so we went there.
They ran off with just all kinds of stuff.
And so the man wrote me after he got back home and said, we don't think we'd keep A&M teams anymore because they ran off all that stuff.
I wrote him back.
I said, well, you know who's in that room and you know what to do.
Just make me a list of that.
And they made me a list of that, and I sent for those boys one at a time.
I said, you're lucky that you're not shipped from school, but you sit right down here and sign this letter that's already written where you apologize for stealing that towel.
And you're going to take it right over here in front of me and put it in this envelope, mail this envelope and this package, which you're going to wrap right now.
And we're going to send that back to the hotel with your apologies for taking it.
And you're not going on any other court trip this year.
You're going to stay here.
I'm putting you in the bullring.
I don't care where he's a senior or where he was a freshman.
If he took something from that room, they must have taken 500 things.
Oh, no.
Let's see.
Oh, we were talking about the election.
When you were mayor and a committee of citizens asked you to run, is that right?
Yes, that's right.
Do you remember that election?
Did anyone run against you?
There was a student.
A student decided to run?
I don't know.
He turned out later on to be a colonel in the army.
But I don't know, he didn't get any votes.
The students couldn't vote.
They didn't know they could if they did.
Well, how did you govern the town since you didn't have a city manager?
I was the city manager.
I was the mayor and city manager.
I helped put in fire plugs, and we didn't order anything, but we had very little that we ordered.
But, and our policeman was the, and I together did the job.
So it must have taken a lot of your time.
It took all, every morning, all morning long, every morning.
For two years.
Were there, had y'all talked about putting in a city manager?
Do you know, it wasn't during your term?
No, we, that happened after,
Ernest took it over.
Two or three years after that, I guess, they got a city manager.
But y'all, you didn't... We never had a city manager, no, no.
During your term, the council and yourself voted the ward system in?
The ward system?
The awards system.
The wards.
W-A-R-D-S, wards?
I don't remember that.
Oh, okay.
Yeah.
All right.
Oh, College Station has always had a lot of emphasis on recreation.
Yes.
Can you tell me why?
Can I have an opinion as to why they have so much recreation?
Well, I think they're just fairly wise people.
See, I'm a coach.
I've given my life to serious recreation.
That is to accomplish something that you think is worthwhile that's hard to get.
I've concentrated on helping boys find themselves and proving they can go somewhere and do things.
Build strength and determination and confidence in the fact that they can do it and win and get ahead of somebody else in a far way, in a far way always.
Now that, I don't know,
I don't know where this place is.
It's a little unusual, but other people have what we have.
They don't have a high school coach like Geesey.
He's a Crocker Jack.
I hope he's the track coach at A&M College sometime, but he can't be because these boys are doing all right that have the job, and he's old as they are, I guess.
But he needs to be rewarded for doing as much as he's doing in athletics.
He has the finest track teams in the state, and he won it.
I think that recreation, it's a change.
It gives you a lift.
We need to use our muscle.
We need to strengthen everything in us.
And the only way to build strength
work it in, play it in, use it, and health, and long life.
Really?
As an example, find yourself.
The city has just got through a movement, the biggest brush fire you ever saw.
You see these shrubs out there?
I'll call you.
I'll send you a file.
503 Fireview, and the trees that are in the front yard, I dug them up and planted them.
We bought that house for $600.
We cut it in two because it had a wing on it, and it was a little bit too big to move to get down there.
So they had to cut it in two and then they moved it down there.
It cost $900 to move it, it cost $600 to build it, to buy it.
But we lived in it until, oh, until our son decided that we just needed a smaller place, easier to take care of and so forth, and so he built this out and said, come on.
I gave that to one of my sons, another one, and...
He sold it later on, but it's still a good house.
Why did the board of directors want you to move off campus?
Everybody.
They made a rule that nobody could live on the campus but the president.
And why was that?
Well, they just didn't want to have to bother building homes for them.
Oh, I see.
See, they probably have 3,500 people.
working for them now.
And they didn't have the space or the money or the inclination.
And they just solved that problem by saying, well, just move off.
Oh, I see.
And so you bought a house?
We bought a house from the college.
An old house that a friend of ours lived in.
It was, well, heck, it cost, you couldn't put that roof on that house now for $600.
It had a slate roof.
It is just like it was.
It'll be that way, I don't know, unless there's some awful big hail burst into it.
It won't leak or it won't wear out.
Well, the campus owned the homes and then certain people could rent them?
The college owned them.
The college built them and paid for them.
And then when they wanted to move them off, they just said, we'll sell it to you.
And they just practically gave them to the people that bought them.
And we bought that home for $600.
Well, there's been, I've been reading newspapers and things, and there's a historic rivalry between College Station and Bryan.
Was that apparent when you were mayor?
Do you have any examples of that?
Oh, it's no worse or no better.
It's just two communities.
You can't get two communities that don't have problems with each other.
They live so close together, everything is kind of mixed in.
We're in one way, we're just one big, one bigger city, but we've got two administrations here and there.
I used to keep my funds and what little I had in the First National Bank, but, and I used to belong to the, to the, to the Quantas Club over there in Bryan.
But then when they had them out here, I just pulled up and came out here.
Just left their bank and I left their clubs and came on out here because this is where I live.
Would people have been happy if Bryan had become their city and asked for the land?
Well, if they'd just wiped out the boundary and had one headquarters and been one city.
It could have been done all right.
We had our friends in Brown.
We had no problems at all, except just the fact that the merchants, when they had a store out here, they didn't want us to go over there and buy stuff.
And when a man built a house out here,
We didn't want Brian to be furnishing electricity, for instance.
Things like that had to be solved.
That was one of them.
Did you encourage any commercial development when you were mayor?
No, none whatsoever.
You wanted it to remain a...
I wouldn't have been good for College Station because
I don't like to go in debt.
When I graduated from college, I borrowed $10 to help me get to the Kansas harvest fields.
I haven't borrowed anybody since.
I don't like to go in debt either.
I haven't.
And we're fairly well off.
We're doing all right.
Things, I've made
more one way or another since I had the job with the college than I did then.
I came out here for $2,400 and after 10 years I'm making $2,700.
Living in a college house, it cost me $20 a month
It didn't belong to that little department.
That little department had two houses.
The head coach had one and I had the other.
So your money went a lot further those days.
We had a cook.
We had a cook.
Had a... We can't afford one now.
We have one twice a week.
But then we had one seven days a week.
And she upraised the kids.
Christmas came along one Christmas.
We went to Mexico City with another couple and left the kids at home with this very dependable good old girl.
colored girl.
We had a servant's house and she lived in there and we furnished the food and everything and paid her four dollars a week.
That was the life in those days.
That was everybody.
They didn't, nobody made any money at A&M College.
Why the, the uh, these assistant professors probably get as much money as Tom Harrington got as president.
When you became mayor, did you have a specific plan for the city?
Did you want to see the city go?
Well, my plan for the city was just do everything you can to have a better school.
I was chairman of the equalization board.
at one time and we just, everybody tried to be a good citizen and support and expand our schools as people came in and we grew.
I've never, I have never felt like that
That the country was, the city or the state or the nation was taking advantage of me, I'd like to pay my taxes.
I don't like to see them wasted, though.
That's the reason I don't like politicians.
I don't like politicians who get Uncle Sam to support their baby at the expense of all the balance of us.
We're going in debt too far.
We're going in debt so fast that
There's a limit.
There's a limit.
We will go in debt to where we'd be where Germany was at the end of the Second World War.
A mark got to where you took a million marks to buy a pound of butter.
Oh, no.
It's terrible.
So if we keep on going like we're going, though, if we do what the Democrats want us to do and spend money like they did spend, now listen.
The Democrats put us where we are.
Reagan didn't put us where we are.
We're going down steeper with Reagan because they had us going down hell so darn fast we can't get stopped.
And he's trying to save us.
He's trying to salvage our liberty.
Can anybody and everybody see what the Soviet Union's doing?
They have conquered all of their part of Europe,
They're now going into Asia.
They've got Cuba.
They've got Nicaragua.
And the whole Central America is in a turmoil.
If they get there, then Mexico may fall next.
And we'll have all of that stuff over there that the Soviet Union can launch an attack from.
They'll put their stuff over there.
Now, if we can get Western Europe to let us put those missiles in to match up everything they've got, we can delay and maybe keep them off of our necks.
If they're allowed to have theirs there, they'll get ready.
And if they keep on growing and we don't invest and match them,
Missiles from missiles, if we get weak and they get much, much stronger, they'll dictate peace to us because they'll tell Europe, who are our allies, we'll pulverize you.
They've already got them up.
They've got those missiles in place and within range of leveling every big city in France and England and Italy.
And they'll say, you make a move toward, we're going to take the United States on.
We're going to make them bite the bullet.
That wouldn't be very good.
And if the Republican Party blocks him from putting those missiles in, that day will come quicker.
If we get ready, they're devils.
They're liars.
They're cheaters.
They're just everything in the world.
They just want to wipe out a free society.
It hurts them.
They're having a hard time because a lot of people don't, they're not popular with a lot of people because they have made the serf a slave.
He was a serf when Ivan was a serf under the Ghazars.
I can remember all those times.
But they just shot all the big landowners.
They called them the kulaks.
They just shot those people to get them out of the way so we could tell the poor folks that are living on that land what they have to do to balance their lives.
And the factories there took them over.
They just shot the people that owned them so that there wouldn't be any problem with them anymore.
And then they told these people, you're going to work.
here and you're going to work there and you're going to support yourselves.
We won't help you any.
We're going to give you enough, but you're working for us.
We're going to skim off the profit.
This man has a garden.
Enough to support and he has chickens and he has a cow.
He has a plow and a hoe.
And he supports himself, but he has to give most of those vegetables and that grain and so forth to the central pot, to the Soviet Union.
And they still can't feed themselves.
Because when you take away the desire for profit, people don't work hard.
They're not happy.
They don't work.
They just piddle.
They do what they have to do to keep being shot or sent to Siberia.
So they're in bad shape.
But they're in worse shape as long as we have freedom.
They want to take our freedom away from us so that the people won't be able to look off and say they're better off than we are.
And that's the reason they want to take us over.
Can I ask you, do you feel like there was a, what was the biggest problem that you faced in your term?
Did you have any problems?
my biggest problem of my whole life.
No, no, your term is mayor.
Your term is mayor.
I don't think I let it bother me.
I don't think I let it bother me.
Did you, was there any great achievement that you felt like College Station achieved?
No, no we just we just paid for the for the light poles and the wires that went between them and the water

stuff pipes that went in the ground to carry the water to them we paid off the stuff we took over from the developers and by that time we were having enough income from the sale of electricity and from the sale of the water we weren't paid we we had a one policeman and we had no city manager
And we weren't getting any money.
We had one girl and we probably paid her $75 a month, I don't know, maybe $60 a month, I don't know.
We didn't have any expenses.
We used the money we took in to pay up, pay these people off that built the, put in the electric lines and the water system and the sewer system.
We paid them off.
The people that live in this house paid for those three things.
They're still paying for them.
people to pay their way rather than go into debt.
We didn't owe a dollar.
Didn't owe a dollar.
Not one dollar did we owe.
Do you like the way that College Station has developed?
The way you see it today?
I'm not criticizing them at all.
I think they're lucky that they didn't have me.
I think they're awful lucky that they didn't have me because
I didn't care.
I wanted the school to grow, but I didn't care a thing about College Station growing other than just give room for the professors.
I see.
You wanted it to remain small, a small college town.
A small college town, yeah.
I told that this man who was down here, and we had this meeting over in Bryan.
Mrs. Magda Parker used to have a

uh place where she fed a lot of people and uh the different the civil clubs met up there and we had this town meeting for their combined for them and here and i told you the man that was the head of the man that was the head of teague say you know about teague he was our representative for many many many years well he was a he was a boy in school
when I was commandant.
And then later on, he got to be a second lieutenant.
He was that when he left A&M.
Then later on, he was ready and had done the work to be a first lieutenant.
And I was the senior officer around this part of the country, and so they had two other colonels to come in.
And we three checked him over and made the recommendation that he get his promotion to first lieutenant.
So that was what I helped do for Congressman Teague.
Now, but I like this one better than that.
I like this man's, what he's doing more than I did for Tiger Teague.
Graham, you're talking about?
Graham, yeah.
I have a letter from him every week or two.
Oh, that's wonderful.
You were called into World War II.
How did the city, did the city do anything to prepare for war?
Did the city, did College Station do anything to prepare for war, for World War II?
Oh yeah, yeah.
We had our committees set up, and we had a lot of people.
We lived right across the street from somebody who dug a pit where they could go in case of a bomb threat or a bomb.
They started bombing anywhere, and they dug a pit and stocked it with so forth, our next-door neighbor.
So there was a movement there to do that.
A few people did it, not many of them.
I never was very much excited over that.
I didn't much think that they were going to do anything like that at that time.
I don't think they're going to do anything like that now.
I think that they wouldn't bother small towns, certainly.
They'd have to, they'd have to hit the big cities though.
In order to win the war, they'd have to do that.
Well, is there anything else that you might want to add about what the concentration was like before or just your term as mayor that I haven't questioned you about?
Everybody's nice to us.
We have a lot of friends and we like it.
I don't take any dish though in their duties.
I don't support anybody that's running for office at College Station.
I don't know enough about them to do that.
And as far as I can tell, everything's going along very well.
Now, nationally, I'm taking more interest because we can't print money.
And the state of Texas or no other state can print money.
But the United States government can print money
And all they have to do is to print a little more of it.
They've printed too much of it already.
The more money they put in circulation, if they pay off debts, and if they pay it, we draw Social Security.
We also draw a retired army.
I stayed in the army between, I stayed active between the two world wars.

I went to camp two weeks, practically every year, and over there we'd have a bunch of A&M artillerymen that graduated here, and they were over there as second lieutenants, or maybe if they were a little older they were first lieutenants, or maybe they might be a captain of the team.
That would be at the A&M artillery group.
I was with the field artillery.
We had two weeks training there.
We worked hard and we had a lot of fun together.
We always played a little.
We always had a nice little party at the end of the thing and it was just a nice experience.
And when World War II came along, they didn't want us.
I don't think they wanted us.
When I got this call, it says now you don't have to come unless you want to.
I think they had really rather that we didn't come, because I was too old to go overseas already, 52.
And I didn't know that.
I didn't know that I wasn't going to be allowed to go overseas, but they sent me and seven other old colonels
who had been loyal and worked good hard with an outfit between the new wars.
They felt like they just owed it to us to give us a chance if they wanted to come to come.
So we did.
There were seven of us and we went up to school and we went through the basic course again.
I'd already been through the artillery school 1917-18 up at Fort Sill and then
This time they sent us back and we took the basic course, which is much easier than that war course was.
And then after they took the basic course, they didn't have anything for us to do, so they just kept us up there on a board.
To do this, investigate that, do this, that, and the other, and there's always something like that going on.
And then to pick people who have been drafted and they want to go to a cadet camp where they maybe be second lieutenants.

get ready to get a promotion you see and so we we had recommended these people that the captains had sent to us we had talked to them and and if we felt like they offered material we had recommended they go to this school things like that they kept us done for a good many months
And then they finally decided, after all, they didn't have anything else much for us to do.
And they sent us up there, and they sent us to different places.
Sent me to Fort Jackson over in North Carolina.
That's where they ought to have left me through the balance of the war.
That's where we were training the recruits, people to fill in, to fill gaps in casualties overseas.
But they decided they'd better send me off there to something after a year or so, and I went to 30th Division.
And they were training, getting ready to go overseas, to Oklahoma, Tennessee.
And I was with them there, and then they sent us up, finished that, they sent us up to Indianapolis.
And we did a little more work over there, and then they sent them overseas.
And here I was about 52, and there was a cutoff.
No, can't go.

And so I went, I said, I've been in the Army now for a good many months, and I'm just drawing colonel's pay and doing something my captain can do, inspect a mess or something like that, or do other things.
And I didn't come in the Army to do that kind of stuff, and I won't go home.
And I've got a job back at A&M College.
And they turned me down.
They did?
Yeah.
And so they offered me a place to go to West Point.
They said, you go up there and be a teacher at West Point.
I said, well, I'm not the type.
I'm a field soldier.
I'm not the type that has a press blouse every week and shiny.
And I just don't fit in to go to West Point.
I'm way beyond that in the Army.
the way I, what I think that an army man at my age should be doing.
And finally, finally I just wrote him another letter and I said, now listen, I'm going to, I'm, thank you honey.
I'm going to really expose you if you don't let me go.
Because you just are making me do something that is degrading as far as a colonel is supposed to be doing.
And you're paying me for doing something I'm not earning the money for.
Now you better just let me loose now."
And they let me go.
Oh my goodness.
I came on back to A&M College and fitted right in and went on just like I'd never been.
As the track coach?
Yeah.
Well um I appreciate this interview.
Well now this is not much about the City of College Station.
Well if you I if you have other things is there some more that we can talk about that that you remember?
There's I uh I don't I don't know I don't know of anything I don't know of anything the the mayor
In those days, well, just like I said, if there was a polecat around, they'd call the city office.
Well, I'd go get my gun.
If there was a mad dog out, well, I'd go get my gun.
What if there was an accident?
